          "id": "organizational-behavior-201-l01-c1",
          "title": "Types of Groups in Organizations",
          "content": "In organizations, we can find two main types of groups: formal and informal. Formal groups are specifically created by the organization to help achieve certain goals and complete tasks efficiently. For instance, a command group is made up of employees who report directly to a manager, ensuring that everyone knows their responsibilities and who to turn to for guidance. Another example is a task force, which is a temporary group formed to work on a particular project that requires collaboration from people across different departments. Committees are also a type of formal group; they are ongoing teams that provide advice and support on various issues within the organization.\nOn the other hand, informal groups arise naturally through social interactions among employees. These groups can include lunch circles, where colleagues gather to share meals and ideas, or interest-based networks that form around shared hobbies or passions. It's fascinating to note that informal groups can significantly influence workplace behavior, sometimes even more than the formal structures put in place by the organization. Therefore, understanding both formal and informal groups is essential for effective management and fostering teamwork. By recognizing the dynamics of these groups, leaders can create a more harmonious and productive work environment.\nContext recap: In organizations, we can find two main types of groups: formal and informal. Formal groups are specifically created by the organization to help achieve certain goals and complete tasks efficiently. For instance, a command group is made up of employees who report directly to a manager, ensuring that everyone knows their responsibilities and who to turn to for guidance. Another example is a task force, which is a temporary group formed to work on a particular project that requires collaboration from people across different departments.\nWhy this matters: Types of Groups in Organizations helps learners in Business connect ideas from Group Dynamics & Team Performance to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
