          "content": "Understanding the difference between teams and groups is essential for anyone interested in how people work together. While all teams are indeed groups, not every group can be classified as a team. A team is unique because it is built around shared goals, interdependent tasks, and a sense of collective accountability among its members. For example, consider a group of accountants who are each filing their own tax returns. This scenario represents a working group, where individuals are focused on their own tasks without the need for collaboration. On the other hand, think about a product development team that is working together to launch a new product. This team collaborates closely, sharing ideas and responsibilities to achieve a common goal, which is what makes it a true team. Jon Katzenbach and Douglas Smith, two experts in the field, defined a team as 'a small number of people with complementary skills who are committed to a common purpose, performance goals, and an approach for which they hold themselves mutually accountable.' This definition emphasizes the vital role of teamwork in reaching shared objectives and highlights how effective teams can lead to greater success than groups that do not work together in this way.\nContext recap: Understanding the difference between teams and groups is essential for anyone interested in how people work together. While all teams are indeed groups, not every group can be classified as a team. A team is unique because it is built around shared goals, interdependent tasks, and a sense of collective accountability among its members. For example, consider a group of accountants who are each filing their own tax returns.\nWhy this matters: Teams vs. Groups helps learners in Business connect ideas from Group Dynamics & Team Performance to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
