          "id": "organizational-behavior-201-l04-c1",
          "title": "Functional vs. Dysfunctional Conflict",
          "content": "Not all conflict is harmful; in fact, some types of conflict can actually be quite beneficial for teams and organizations. This is known as functional conflict, or constructive conflict. Functional conflict can enhance decision-making processes by challenging existing assumptions, sparking creativity, and bringing to light perspectives that may have been overlooked. One specific type of functional conflict is task conflict, which involves disagreements about the work itself. When managed effectively, task conflict can lead to productive discussions and better outcomes.\nOn the other hand, there are types of conflict that tend to be more harmful. Relationship conflict arises from personal friction and animosity between team members, and it is usually destructive to team dynamics. Another type of conflict is process conflict, which involves disputes about how to carry out the work. This type of conflict can be more neutral, falling somewhere in between functional and dysfunctional conflict.\nThe key to effectively managing conflict within a team is to find the right balance. If there is too little conflict, it can lead to apathy and groupthink, where team members may not feel encouraged to share their ideas or challenge each other. Conversely, if there is too much conflict, it can create hostility and paralysis, making it difficult for the team to move forward. Therefore, understanding the different types of conflict and how to manage them is essential for fostering a healthy team environment.\nContext recap: Not all conflict is harmful; in fact, some types of conflict can actually be quite beneficial for teams and organizations. This is known as functional conflict, or constructive conflict. Functional conflict can enhance decision-making processes by challenging existing assumptions, sparking creativity, and bringing to light perspectives that may have been overlooked. One specific type of functional conflict is task conflict, which involves disagreements about the work itself.\nWhy this matters: Functional vs. Dysfunctional Conflict helps learners in Business connect ideas from Group Dynamics & Team Performance to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
